<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-antilogarithms"  xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Antilogarithms</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_cf5igd0a">
            <p xml:id="auto_tdjj63tf">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_151pu9l0">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_euiaaj9d">
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_ngdxzwkl">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_w6cmokir">
                        1.2 Indices and Logarithms
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_7bph74r2">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_j6wypvwh">
                        Determine common logarithms of numbers from mathematical tables and calculators
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5u9ulm0u" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_xv170b0r">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_w8mmo1we" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_xgjo7n86">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_sy52ye6a" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_pmkmtdih"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_2tdj3bxl">
                        <p xml:id="auto_727ve2u8">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand that antilogarithm is the inverse operation of logarithm, and recognize the relationship between logarithms and exponentials.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_0i7evi3g">
                        <p xml:id="auto_0kl6xos9">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Find antilogarithms using logarithm tables and scientific calculators by separating characteristic and mantissa.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_bm8mf9sp">
                        <p xml:id="auto_sm6t06gi">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Apply antilogarithm skills to solve equations and verify logarithmic calculations.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_g3n20udm">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/indices-and-logarithms/antilogarithms.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_jy061x3o">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/indices-and-logarithms/step-by-step-guide_antilogarithms.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery / Engage &amp; Explore</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_1h8gvnv9">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_7xmworxe">
            <alert>Objective:</alert> To explore the inverse relationship between logarithms and antilogarithms.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ko6un1dy">
            <alert>Anchor Learning Experience: Discovering the Inverse Operation</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_qpn5dtjl">
            <alert>Part A: Understanding Inverse Operations</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_g5ct7zr0">
            Students recall that addition/subtraction and multiplication/division are inverse operations. They then explore: What is the inverse operation of taking a logarithm?
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_4uksynby">
            <alert>Part B: Exploring the Pattern</alert>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_dole4w0x">
            Students complete a table:
        </p>
        <tabular bottom="medium" top="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
            <row header="yes">
                <cell>Logarithm</cell>
                <cell>Value</cell>
                <cell>Reverse Operation</cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>\log(100) =</m></cell>
                <cell>2</cell>
                <cell>If <m>\log(x) = 2</m>, then <m>x = ?</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>\log(1000) =</m></cell>
                <cell>3</cell>
                <cell>If <m>\log(x) = 3</m>, then <m>x = ?</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>\log(47.3) =</m></cell>
                <cell>1.6749</cell>
                <cell>If <m>\log(x) = 1.6749</m>, then <m>x = ?</m></cell>
            </row>
            <row>
                <cell><m>\log(473) =</m></cell>
                <cell>2.6749</cell>
                <cell>If <m>\log(x) = 2.6749</m>, then <m>x = ?</m></cell>
            </row>
        </tabular>
        <p xml:id="auto_zjht6nkm">
            <alert>Discussion Questions:</alert>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_soo1zsvd"><p xml:id="auto_kugdnlbu">What pattern do you notice between the logarithm value and the original number?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_lwjlotw5"><p xml:id="auto_2z567725">How can you <q>undo</q> a logarithm to get back the original number?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_qtd4le6r"><p xml:id="auto_cfig7jv9">What is the relationship between <m>\log(x) = y</m> and <m>x = 10^y</m>?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_71xlovlb"><p xml:id="auto_7wqo1l8j">How might you use the logarithm table <q>backwards</q> to find antilogarithms?</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_q6b1lif1">
            <alert>Teacher's Role:</alert> The teacher circulates among groups, asking probing questions (e.g., <q>If <m>\log(100) = 2</m>, what operation gives you back 100?</q>, <q>How is <m>10^2</m> related to <m>\log(100) = 2</m>?</q>). The teacher uses student discoveries to bridge to formal instruction.
        </p>
    </axiom>


    <p xml:id="auto_fupjnet2">
        The antilogarithm (antilog) of a number is the inverse operation of taking a logarithm. If <m>\log x = y</m>, then <m>x</m> is the antilog of <m>y</m>. This means:
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_kiuh5wvd">
        <me>
            x = 10^y
        </me>
    </p>
    <p xml:id="auto_21gukbqe">
        To find the antilogarithm of a number, we use logarithm tables or a calculator.
    </p>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>Finding Antilogarithms Using Logarithm Tables</title>
        <activity xml:id="auto_axsj8pw9">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_vf3rgyog">
                    <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of <m>2</m> or <m>3</m> students.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ymoh17c8">
                    <term>Materials:</term> Logarithm table, paper and pen
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_shwvxjcz">
                    <term>Instructions:</term>
                </p>
                <ol marker="(a)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_zg2ph68w">
                        Rewrite <m>\log(100) = 2</m> and <m>\log(1000) = 3</m> in exponential form.
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_mw850o8e">
                        If <m>\log(x) = 2.6756</m>, write this in exponential form.
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_83rcnw1w">
                        Separate <m>2.6756</m> into its characteristic and mantissa.
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_6h7lxw7r">
                        Using the logarithm table, find the antilog of the mantissa.
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_21o579if">
                        Apply the characteristic as a power of <m>10</m> to obtain the value of <m>x</m>.
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_imerqzrv">
                        Verify your result by taking the logarithm of your answer.
                    </li>
                </ol>
                <p xml:id="auto_56iauzti">
                    What role does the characteristic play? What role does the mantissa play?
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>

        <insight xml:id="auto_8rleg62c">
            <p xml:id="auto_5j2kygk7">
                A logarithm can be reversed by raising the base to the given power.
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_ocphftgh">
                If:
            <me>
                    \log(x) = y
            </me>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_nrcg6zll">
                then:
            <me>
                    x = 10^y
            </me>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_im5r3ssf">
                The operation of finding <m>x</m> from <m>y</m> is called the <term>antilogarithm</term>.
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_l55ucmii">
                When using tables:
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_543k8cbg">
                <ol marker="1)">
                    <li xml:id="auto_1473kt47">Separate the <term>characteristic</term> (integer part).</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_3sllgk6b">Use the table to find the antilog of the <term>mantissa</term> (decimal part).</li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_siih8osj">Multiply by <m>10^{\text{characteristic}}</m>.</li>
                </ol>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_5yt3p7jq">
                The mantissa determines the significant digits,
                while the characteristic determines the position of the decimal point.
            </p>
        </insight>

        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
            <title>Structured Instruction </title>
            <p xml:id="auto_qdcq8pbb">
                <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 10 minutes
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_sq47phl9">
                <alert>Objective:</alert> To formalize the concept and procedure for finding antilogarithms.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_h9zw4ckd">
                <alert>Key Takeaways:</alert>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_elhaln3i">
                <alert>What is an Antilogarithm?</alert> The antilogarithm (or antilog) is the INVERSE operation of the logarithm. If <m>\log(x) = y</m>, then <m>\text{antilog}(y) = x</m>. In other words: <m>\text{antilog}(y) = 10^y</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_3q3iqck9">
                <alert>The Fundamental Relationship:</alert>
            </p>
            <tabular bottom="medium" top="medium" left="medium" right="medium">
                <row header="yes">
                    <cell>Logarithm</cell>
                    <cell>Antilogarithm</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell><m>\log(x) = y</m></cell>
                    <cell><m>\text{antilog}(y) = x = 10^y</m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p xml:id="auto_uqtu62jn">
                <alert>Finding Antilogarithms Using Tables (3-Step Process):</alert>
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_xlzkizdm"><p xml:id="auto_u1xc6ls7">Separate the characteristic (integer part) and mantissa (decimal part)</p></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_svdpmpf6"><p xml:id="auto_36rv76l7">Find the antilog of the mantissa from the antilog table</p></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_etstsab2"><p xml:id="auto_harputrb">Multiply by <m>10^{\text{characteristic}}</m></p></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_k1kkr5v5">
                <alert>Finding Antilogarithms Using a Calculator:</alert> Use the <m>10^x</m> button (or INV + LOG), or enter <m>10^{\text{value}}</m> directly.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_0gakyqx3">
                <alert>Important Inverse Properties:</alert>
                <ul>
                    <li xml:id="auto_djo4x2oy"><p xml:id="auto_nfhilf06"><m>\log_a(a^x) = x</m> — Taking log <q>undoes</q> the exponent</p></li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_e64kmknt"><p xml:id="auto_s7n680v3"><m>a^{\log_a(x)} = x</m> — Raising to power <q>undoes</q> the log</p></li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_8wzg1f8z">
                Examples: <m>\log_5(625) = \log_5(5^4) = 4</m>; <m>5^{\log_5(22)} = 22</m>.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_4hve7pfn">
                <alert>Addressing Misconceptions:</alert> <q>Remember: The antilog table is read differently from the log table. Also, antilog is NOT the same as negative log — it's the inverse operation!</q>
            </p>
        </axiom>

        <example xml:id="auto_n92jroxz">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_72ayiu13">
                    Find the antilogarithm of <m>2.6756</m> using logarithm tables.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_vcy4ysuj">
                    Separate the characteristic and mantissa
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_opo8pvhl">
                    <me>
                        2.6756 = 2 + 0.6756
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_9qwimd81">
                    Find the antilogarithm of <m>0.6756</m> using tables:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_lv9k9ff2">
                    <me>
                        \text{Antilog } (0.6756) = 4.735
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ytllhlmi">
                    Apply the characteristic:
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_qtdsbo48">
                    <me>
                        10^2 \times 4.735 = 473.5
                    </me>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ntqsxk8e">
                    Thus, the antilogarithm of <m>2.6756</m> is <m>473.5</m>.
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
    </paragraphs>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_8at2tu8g">
            <alert>Suggested Time:</alert> 15 minutes
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_kr5xnh6z">
            <alert>Objective:</alert> To apply antilogarithm skills using tables and calculators.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_p1yvcz59">
            <alert>Learning Experience:</alert> Students work through the worked example finding <m>\text{antilog}(2.6756)</m> using tables: separating into characteristic 2 and mantissa 0.6756, looking up the antilog of the mantissa (4.735), and multiplying by <m>10^2</m> to get 473.5. They also practise using the inverse properties: <m>\log_5(625) = \log_5(5^4) = 4</m> and <m>5^{\log_5(22)} = 22</m>.
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_veeph1ro">
            <alert>Teacher's Role:</alert> The teacher monitors students, emphasizing the importance of correctly separating characteristic and mantissa, and verifying answers.
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <paragraphs>
        <title>Finding Antilogarithms Using a Calculator</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_qduphmts">
            When using a calculator, simply input the given logarithm value and use the inverse logarithm function:
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_w0mf7d3r">
            <me>
                x = 10^y
            </me>
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_ni9x43uw">
            <term>For example,</term> to find <m>\text{Antilog } (1.3562)</m> on a calculator:
        </p>
        <p xml:id="auto_txqh6h3o">
            <ul xml:id="auto_48qp54c3">
                <li xml:id="auto_rmpfanyt">
                    <p xml:id="auto_vf9lajq2">
                        Press <kbd>10^x</kbd> or <kbd>INV</kbd> + <kbd>LOG</kbd> and enter <m>1.3562</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_p6c7y0wr">
                    <p xml:id="auto_2jn55u2z">
                        Record the results
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </paragraphs>

